   <abstract >Screening benefits both individuals and systems, enabling early identification of treatable conditions at scale. In education, schools use a variety of assessments and approaches to screen for risk of dyslexia or reading difficulties, and these vary in terms of technical adequacy and ease of administration. Screening assessments are commonly evaluated in terms of classification accuracy, with ideal assessments having at least a sensitivity of .90 and a specificity of .80. A recent study demonstrated that the correlation between a screening assessment and criterion outcome assessment can be used in combination with the base rate of the target condition to derive classification accuracy without actually applying the assessment to a sample. This study demonstrated that a univariate (single indicator) screening assessment could not achieve ideal classification accuracy unless the screener-outcome correlation was at or above .85. Because this level of predictive validity is unrealistically high for a univariate screener, the present study used a series of simulations to test how adding an additional indicator affects the screener-outcome correlation needed to achieve ideal classification accuracy, and compares this threshold across screening approaches (e.g., single-timepoint versus gated screening). Results showed that one- and two-indicator screening approaches using cut-points to assign risk can almost never achieve ideal classification accuracy as commonly defined, particularly when the base rate in the sample is low. Further, the specific approach used to assign risk affected classification accuracy and predictive power. Implications for the recommendations given to schools regarding universal screening and future directions for research are discussed.</abstract>
